---
// src/components/chrome/DrawerTrigger.astro — M-UX T7 deliverable.
//
// Hamburger button that opens / closes the mobile drawer.
//
// **Mount position (M-UX T7 → M-UX-REVIEW T4 D1).**
// Cycle 1 (M-UX T7) mounted the trigger inside `Breadcrumb.astro`'s
// `drawer-trigger` named slot so the breadcrumb's flexbox layout
// owned its placement. M-UX-REVIEW T4 D1 (UI-review F9) hides the
// breadcrumb at <768px (`.breadcrumb-bar { display: none }`) — the
// trigger has to survive that hide. T4 picks Option A from the spec:
// extract the trigger so it mounts as a SIBLING of the breadcrumb in
// `Base.astro` (via the new `drawer-trigger` named slot), giving the
// trigger a stable parent regardless of viewport. The breadcrumb's
// own `drawer-trigger` slot is gone post-T4. Communication contract
// with `Drawer.astro` is unchanged — same `cs300:drawer-toggle`
// CustomEvent.
//
// **Two-component split.** The actual drawer overlay (the aside +
// backdrop + open/close logic) lives in `Drawer.astro`, mounted at
// body level via `Base.astro`'s `slot="drawer"`. This file is
// trigger-only. See `Drawer.astro`'s header docstring for the
// rationale: a single Astro component cannot route to two parent
// slots simultaneously, but the breakout audit firmly fixes the
// BUTTON near the chrome top (visible at <1024px) and the ASIDE at
// body root (so the drawer's `position: fixed` element escapes the
// sticky-breadcrumb's `z-index: 50` stacking context).
//
// **Communication** (per `Drawer.astro` header):
// click dispatches `cs300:drawer-toggle` CustomEvent; the sibling
// `Drawer.astro` island listens. No detail payload — toggle (open
// if closed, close if open). Same custom-event idiom as the rest
// of M3 / M-UX (`cs300:read-status-changed`, `cs300:annotation-
// added`, `cs300:toc-read-status-painted`).
//
// **Visibility gate** (T7 spec step 1 line 26 + step 16 "Hamburger
// visible only at <1024px"): the @media (max-width: 1023.98px)
// rule on the button itself flips display from `none` to
// `inline-flex`. At ≥1024px the button is removed from layout AND
// from the tab order so keyboard users at desktop don't reach a
// dead trigger.
//
// **Accessibility** (T7 spec step 7 + T4 D3 chevron rule):
//   - `aria-controls="drawer"` ties the button to the aside.
//   - `aria-expanded` reflects open state — toggled by Drawer.astro
//     in its open() / close() functions.
//   - `aria-label="Open navigation"` reads as a friendly name for
//     screen readers. The visible "Chapters" label is decorative;
//     the icon and chevron carry `aria-hidden="true"` so the SR
//     announcement stays "Open navigation, collapsed/expanded".
//   - `id="drawer-trigger"` is the focus-restore target on close
//     (Drawer.astro's lastFocused fallback).
//
// **M-UX-REVIEW T4 D3 — label + chevron (UI-review F10).**
// Cycle 1 markup was a bare `<button>☰</button>`. T4 adds:
//   - `<span class="drawer-icon">☰</span>` — preserved from cycle 1
//     (renamed from `.drawer-trigger-icon` for terser CSS).
//   - `<span class="drawer-label">Chapters</span>` — visible label
//     so first-open users know what the drawer contains. Hidden via
//     `@media (max-width: 359.98px)` so very narrow phones (320px
//     legacy iPhone SE 1st-gen, etc.) don't crowd the breadcrumb /
//     trigger row; icon + chevron stay visible.
//   - `<span class="drawer-chevron" aria-hidden="true">›</span>` —
//     visual state indicator. CSS rotates 180° when the trigger has
//     `data-drawer-state="open"` (set by Drawer.astro on the same
//     toggle path that flips `aria-expanded`).
//
// `data-drawer-state` is the styling hook (CSS-only rotation).
// `aria-expanded` remains the a11y hook. Two attributes on the
// trigger because rotating via the `[aria-expanded="true"]` selector
// would couple visuals to the a11y state — Drawer.astro flips both
// in lockstep so the dual attributes never disagree, but keeping the
// styling hook distinct means a future a11y refactor (e.g. adopting
// `aria-controls` discoverability) can move the a11y attribute
// without re-styling the chevron.
//
// Companion files:
//   - design_docs/milestones/m_ux_polish/tasks/T7_mobile_drawer.md
//   - design_docs/milestones/m_ux_review/tasks/T4_mobile_reduction.md
//   - src/components/chrome/Drawer.astro (T7 sibling — the overlay;
//     T4 updates to flip `data-drawer-state` alongside `aria-expanded`)
//   - src/layouts/Base.astro (T4 — the new `drawer-trigger` named slot)
//   - src/components/chrome/Breadcrumb.astro (T4 — the in-breadcrumb
//     `drawer-trigger` slot is gone; trigger no longer mounts here)
---

<button
  type="button"
  id="drawer-trigger"
  class="drawer-trigger"
  data-drawer-state="closed"
  aria-controls="drawer"
  aria-expanded="false"
  aria-label="Open navigation"
>
  <span class="drawer-icon" aria-hidden="true">☰</span>
  <span class="drawer-label">Chapters</span>
  <span class="drawer-chevron" aria-hidden="true">›</span>
</button>

<style>
  /* Tokens come from src/styles/chrome.css (imported globally by
     Base.astro). */
  .drawer-trigger {
    /* Hidden at desktop — drawer affordance is mobile-only. The
       1024px breakpoint matches `Base.astro`'s grid breakpoint
       (chrome.css `--mux-bp-desktop`). 1023.98px keeps the rule
       tight against the desktop boundary so a viewport at exactly
       1024px gets the desktop layout. */
    display: none;
    appearance: none;
    background: transparent;
    border: 1px solid var(--mux-border-subtle);
    border-radius: 4px;
    padding: var(--mux-space-1) var(--mux-space-3);
    color: var(--mux-fg);
    cursor: pointer;
    line-height: 1;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    /* Inner gap between icon / label / chevron when the button is
       displayed at <1024px. Inert at desktop because the button is
       hidden there. */
    gap: var(--mux-space-2);
  }

  .drawer-trigger:hover {
    background: var(--mux-surface-alt);
  }

  .drawer-trigger:focus-visible {
    outline: 2px solid var(--mux-accent);
    outline-offset: 2px;
  }

  .drawer-icon {
    /* The hamburger glyph itself. `aria-hidden` on the parent span
       (markup above) keeps screen readers from announcing the
       three-bar character. */
    display: inline-block;
    line-height: 1;
    font-size: 1.1rem;
  }

  .drawer-label {
    /* Visible "Chapters" text. Sized down from the icon so the
       composite reads as a labelled icon, not as a sentence. */
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    line-height: 1;
  }

  .drawer-chevron {
    /* CSS-rotated state indicator. T4 D3 spec calls for a 180°
       rotation when the drawer opens; the `›` glyph rotated 180°
       reads as `‹`, which is the desired closed-when-open affordance.
       Transition is the only motion we add — matches the rest of
       M-UX's "instant where possible" rule (drawer slide is the
       single animated chrome surface). */
    display: inline-block;
    line-height: 1;
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: var(--mux-fg-subtle);
    transition: transform 150ms ease;
  }

  /* Open state — flip the chevron. Drawer.astro flips
     `data-drawer-state` to "open" on the same toggle path that flips
     `aria-expanded`. Pure CSS rotation, no JS animation. */
  .drawer-trigger[data-drawer-state="open"] .drawer-chevron {
    transform: rotate(180deg);
  }

  @media (max-width: 1023.98px) {
    .drawer-trigger {
      display: inline-flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
    }
  }

  /* Very narrow phones — hide the "Chapters" label so the trigger
     stays compact on 320-360px legacy widths. Icon + chevron remain.
     T4 D3 spec calls for this hide threshold. */
  @media (max-width: 359.98px) {
    .drawer-label {
      display: none;
    }
  }
</style>

<script>
  /**
   * Trigger script — emits `cs300:drawer-toggle` on click. The
   * Drawer.astro island catches the event and runs the open/close
   * logic. Inline `<script>` so the trigger is interactive on first
   * paint; matches the rest of M-UX/M3's no-framework JS island
   * pattern.
   */
  const trigger = document.getElementById('drawer-trigger');
  trigger?.addEventListener('click', () => {
    window.dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent('cs300:drawer-toggle'));
  });
</script>
